aa(lp253
VOne of the things that's happened because of this
p254
aVis that, since 1969,
p255
aVthe country of Nigeria, or the part of Nigeria that pumps oil,
p256
aVwhich is the delta \u2014 which is two times the size of Maryland \u2014
p257
aVhas had thousands of oil spills a year.
p258
aVI mean, we've essentially been exporting oil spills
p259
aVwhen we import oil from places
p260
aVwithout tight environmental regulations.
p261
aVThat has been the equivalent of an Exxon Valdez spill
p262
aVevery year since 1969.
p263
aVAnd we can wrap our heads around the spills,
p264
aVbecause that's what we see here,
p265
aVbut in fact, these guys actually live in a war zone.
p266
aVThere's a thousand battle-related deaths a year
p267
aVin this area twice the size of Maryland,
p268
aVand it's all related to the oil.
p269
aVAnd these guys, I mean, if they were in the U.S.,
p270
aVthey might be actually here in this room.
p271
aVThey have degrees in political science, degrees in business \u2014
p272
aVthey're entrepreneurs. They don't actually want to be doing what they're doing.
p273
aVAnd it's sort of one of the other groups of people
p274
aVwho pay a price for us.
p275
aa(lp276
VThe other thing that we've done,
p277
aVas we've continued to increase demand,
p278
aVis that we kind of play a shell game with the costs.
p279
aVOne of the places we put in a big oil project
p280
aVin Chad, with Exxon.
p281
aVSo the U.S. taxpayer paid for it;
p282
aVthe World Bank, Exxon paid for it.
p283
aVWe put it in. There was a tremendous banditry problem.
p284
aVI was there in 2003.
p285
aVWe were driving along this dark, dark road,
p286
aVand the guy in the green stepped out,
p287
aVand I was just like, "Ahhh! This is it."
p288
aVAnd then the guy in the Exxon uniform stepped out,
p289
aVand we realized it was okay.
p290
aVThey have their own private sort of army around them at the oil fields.
p291
aVBut at the same time,
p292
aVChad has become much more unstable,
p293
aVand we are not paying for that price at the pump.
p294
aVWe pay for it in our taxes on April 15th.
p295
aa(lp296
VWe do the same thing
p297
aVwith the price of policing the Persian Gulf
p298
aVand keeping the shipping lanes open.
p299
aVThis is 1988 \u2014
p300
aVwe actually bombed two Iranian oil platforms that year.
p301
aVThat was the beginning of an escalating U.S. involvement there
p302
aVthat we do not pay for at the pump.
p303
aVWe pay for it on April 15th,
p304
aVand we can't even calculate the cost of this involvement.
p305
aVThe other place that is sort of supporting our dependence on oil
p306
aVand our increased consumption
p307
aVis the Gulf of Mexico,
p308
aVwhich was not part of the moratoriums.
p309
aVNow what's happened in the Gulf of Mexico \u2014 as you can see,
p310
aVthis is the Minerals Management diagram
p311
aVof wells for gas and oil.
p312
aVIt's become this intense industrialized zone.
p313
aVIt doesn't have the same resonance for us
p314
aVthat the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge has,
p315
aVbut it should, I mean, it's a bird sanctuary.
