p369
aVand make them much more efficient,
p370
aVbut we also need to fix the economy in general.
p371
aa(lp372
VWe need to remove the perverse incentives to use more fuel.
p373
aVFor example, we have an insurance system
p374
aVwhere the person who drives 20,000 miles a year
p375
aVpays the same insurance as somebody who drives 3,000.
p376
aVWe actually encourage people to drive more.
p377
aVWe have policies that reward sprawl \u2014 we have all kinds of policies.
p378
aVWe need to have more mobility choices.
p379
aVWe need to make the gas price
p380
aVbetter reflect the real cost of oil.
p381
aVAnd we need to shift subsidies from the oil industry,
p382
aVwhich is at least 10 billion dollars a year,
p383
aVinto something that allows middle-class people to find better ways to commute.
p384
aVWhether that's getting a much more efficient car
p385
aVand also kind of building markets
p386
aVfor new cars and new fuels down the road,
p387
aVthis is where we need to be.
p388
aVWe need to kind of rationalize this whole thing,
p389
aVand you can find more about this policy.
p390
aVIt's called STRONG, which is "Secure Transportation
p391
aVReducing Oil Needs Gradually,"
p392
aVand the idea is instead of being helpless, we need to be more strong.
p393
aVThey're up at NewAmerica.net.
p394
aVWhat's important about these
p395
aVis that we try to move
p396
aVfrom feeling helpless at the pump,
p397
aVto actually being active
p398
aVand to really sort of thinking about who we are,
p399
aVhaving kind of that special moment,
p400
aVwhere we connect the dots actually at the pump.
